That’s a strong play on the word.

“History” as:

his story

—the narratives people inherit, repeat, compress, mythologize, and build civilizations around.

Not literally that history is only one person’s account, but that human memory and culture are always filtered through perspective, selection, emphasis, and storytelling structure.

The interesting part is that stories become coordination tools:

* they transmit values
* compress lessons
* create identity
* justify action
* preserve continuity across generations

A nation, family, company, religion, or brand often survives partly because of the stories it tells about itself.

And once enough people attach to the same narrative, it starts shaping real behavior in the world:

* markets move
* wars happen
* fashions spread
* technologies get funded
* communities form

So even imperfect stories can have very real causal force.